The [[Session Initiation Protocol]] (SIP) is a [[signalling (telecommunications)|signalling]] [[communications protocol|protocol]] used for controlling communication sessions such as [[Voice over IP]] [[telephone call]]s. SIP is based around request/response transactions, in a similar manner to the [[Hypertext Transfer Protocol]] (HTTP). Each transaction consists of a SIP request (which will be one of several [[List of SIP request methods|request methods]]), and at least one response.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|p11}}
SIP requests and responses may be generated by any SIP [[user agent]]; user agents are divided into clients (UACs), which initiate requests, and servers (UASes), which respond to them.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§8}} A single user agent may act as both UAC and UAS for different transactions:<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|p26}} for example, a [[SIP phone]] is a user agent that will be a UAC when making a call, and a UAS when receiving one. Additionally, some devices will act as both UAC and UAS for a single transaction; these are called Back-to-Back User Agents (B2BUAs).<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|p20}}
SIP responses specify a three-digit integer response code, which is one of a number of defined codes that detail the status of the request. These codes are grouped according to their first digit as "provisional", "success", "redirection", "client error", "server error" or "global failure" codes, corresponding to a first digit of 1–6; these are expressed as, for example, "1xx" for provisional responses with a code of 100–199.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§7.2}} The SIP response codes are consistent with the [[List of HTTP status codes|HTTP response codes]], although not all HTTP response codes are valid in SIP.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21}}
SIP responses also specify a "reason phrase", and a default reason phrase is defined with each response code.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§7.2}} These reason phrases can be varied, however, such as to provide additional information<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.18}} or to provide the text in a different language.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§20.3}}
The SIP response codes and corresponding reason phrases were initially defined in RFC 3261.<ref name="RFC_3261"/> That RFC also defines a SIP Parameters [[Internet Assigned Numbers Authority]] (IANA) registry to allow other RFC to provide more response codes.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§27}}<ref name="IANA"/>
This list includes all the SIP response codes defined in [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] [[Request for Comment|RFC]]s and registered in the SIP Parameters IANA registry {{as of|2017|07|14|lc=y}}. This list also includes SIP response codes defined in obsolete SIP RFCs (specifically, RFC 2543), which are therefore not registered with the IANA; these are explicitly noted as such.
==1xx—Provisional Responses== ;{{anchor|100}} 100 Trying : Extended search being performed may take a significant time so a forking proxy must send a 100 Trying response.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.1.1}} ;{{anchor|180}} 180 Ringing : Destination user agent received INVITE, and is alerting user of call.<ref name="RFC_3261">{{cite IETF | title = SIP: Session Initiation Protocol | rfc = 3261 | last1 = Rosenberg | first1 = Jonathan | last2 = Schulzrinne | first2 = Henning | authorlink2 = Henning Schulzrinne | last3 = Camarillo | first3 = Gonzalo | last4 = Johnston | first4 = Alan | last5 = Peterson | first5 = Jon | last6 = Sparks | first6 = Robert | last7 = Handley | first7 = Mark | authorlink7 = Mark Handley (computer scientist) | last8 = Schooler | first8 = Eve | year = 2002 | month = June | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] }}</ref>{{rp|§21.1.2}} ;{{anchor|181}} 181 Call is Being Forwarded : Servers can optionally send this response to indicate a call is being forwarded.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.1.3}} ;{{anchor|182}} 182 Queued : Indicates that the destination was temporarily unavailable, so the server has queued the call until the destination is available. A server may send multiple 182 responses to update progress of the queue.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.1.4}} ;{{anchor|183}} 183 Session Progress : This response may be used to send extra information for a call which is still being set up.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.1.5}} ;{{anchor|199}} 199 Early Dialog Terminated : Can be used by User Agent Server to indicate to upstream SIP entities (including the User Agent Client (UAC)) that an early dialog has been terminated.<ref name="RFC_6228">{{cite IETF | title = Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Response Code for Indication of Terminated Dialog | rfc = 6228 | last = Holmberg | first = Christer | year = 2011 | month = May | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | section = Abstract | nosec = y | page = 1 }}</ref>
== 2xx—Successful Responses == ;{{anchor|200}} 200 OK : Indicates the request was successful.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.2.1}} ;{{anchor|202}} 202 Accepted : Indicates that the request has been accepted for processing, but the processing has not been completed.<ref name="RFC_3265">{{cite IETF | title = Session Initiation Protocol (SIP)-Specific Event Notification | rfc = 3265 | last = Roach | first = Adam B. | year = 2002 | month = June | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] }}</ref>{{rp|§7.3.1}}<ref name="RFC_2616">{{cite IETF | title = Hypertext Transfer Protocol -- HTTP/1.1 | rfc = 2616 | last1 = Fielding | first1 = Roy T. | authorlink1 = Roy Fielding | last2 = Gettys | first2 = James | last3 = Mogul | first3 = Jeffrey C. | last4 = Nielsen | first4 = Henrik Frystyk | authorlink4 = Henrik Frystyk Nielsen | last5 = Masinter | first5 = Larry | last6 = Leach | first6 = Paul | last7 = Berners-Lee | first7 = Tim | authorlink7 = Tim Berners-Lee | year = 1999 | month = June | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | sectionname = 202 Accepted | section = 10.2.3 }}</ref> Deprecated.<ref name="RFC_6665">{{cite IETF | title = SIP-Specific Event Notification | rfc = 6665 | last = Roach | first = Adam | year = 2012 | month = July | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] }}</ref>{{rp|§8.3.1}}<ref name="IANA">{{cite web | url = https://www.iana.org/assignments/sip-parameters/sip-parameters.xhtml#sip-parameters-7 | title = Response Codes | work = Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Parameters | publisher = [[Internet Assigned Numbers Authority|IANA]] | last1 = Roach | first1 = Adam | last2 = Jennings | first2 = Cullen | last3 = Peterson | first3 = Jon | last4 = Barnes | first4 = Mary | date = 17 April 2013 | origyear = Created January 2002 }}</ref> ;{{anchor|204}} 204 No Notification : Indicates the request was successful, but the corresponding response will not be received.<ref name="RFC_5839">{{cite IETF | title = An Extension to Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Events for Conditional Event Notification | rfc = 5839 | last = Niemi | first = Aki | editor-last = Willis | editor-first = Dean | year = 2010 | month = May | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | sectionname = 204 (No Notification) Response Code | section = 7.1 }}</ref>
== 3xx—Redirection Responses == ;{{anchor|300}} 300 Multiple Choices : The address resolved to one of several options for the user or client to choose between, which are listed in the message body or the message's Contact fields.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.3.1}} ;{{anchor|301}} 301 Moved Permanently : The original Request-URI is no longer valid, the new address is given in the Contact header field, and the client should update any records of the original Request-URI with the new value.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.3.2}} ;{{anchor|302}} 302 Moved Temporarily : The client should try at the address in the Contact field. If an Expires field is present, the client may cache the result for that period of time.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.3.3}} ;{{anchor|305}} 305 Use Proxy : The Contact field details a proxy that must be used to access the requested destination.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.3.4}} ;{{anchor|380}} 380 Alternative Service : The call failed, but alternatives are detailed in the message body.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.3.5}}
== 4xx—Client Failure Responses == ;{{anchor|400}} 400 Bad Request : The request could not be understood due to malformed syntax.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.1}} ;{{anchor|401}} 401 Unauthorized : The request requires user authentication. This response is issued by UASs and registrars.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.2}} ;{{anchor|402}} 402 Payment Required : Reserved for future use.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.3}} ;{{anchor|403}} 403 Forbidden : The server understood the request, but is refusing to fulfill it.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.4}} Sometimes (but not always) this means the call has been rejected by the receiver. ;{{anchor|404}} 404 Not Found : The server has definitive information that the user does not exist at the domain specified in the Request-URI. This status is also returned if the domain in the Request-URI does not match any of the domains handled by the recipient of the request.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.5}} ;{{anchor|405}} 405 Method Not Allowed : The method specified in the Request-Line is understood, but not allowed for the address identified by the Request-URI.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.6}} ;{{anchor|406}} 406 Not Acceptable : The resource identified by the request is only capable of generating response entities that have content characteristics but not acceptable according to the Accept header field sent in the request.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.7}} ;{{anchor|407}} 407 Proxy Authentication Required : The request requires user authentication. This response is issued by proxys.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.8}} ;{{anchor|408}} 408 Request Timeout : Couldn't find the user in time. The server could not produce a response within a suitable amount of time, for example, if it could not determine the location of the user in time. The client MAY repeat the request without modifications at any later time. <ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.9}} ;{{anchor|409}} 409 Conflict : User already registered.<ref name="RFC_2543">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | title = SIP: Session Initiation Protocol | rfc = 2543 | last1 = Handley | first1 = Mark | authorlink1 = Mark Handley (computer scientist) | last2 = Schulzrinne | first2 = Henning | authorlink2 = Henning Schulzrinne | last3 = Schooler | first3 = Eve | last4 = Rosenberg | first4 = Jonathan | year = 1999 | month = March }}</ref>{{rp|§7.4.10}} Deprecated by omission from later RFCs<ref name="RFC_3261"/> and by non-registration with the IANA.<ref name="IANA"/> ;{{anchor|410}} 410 Gone : The user existed once, but is not available here any more.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.10}} ;{{anchor|411}} 411 Length Required : The server will not accept the request without a valid Content-Length.<ref name="RFC_2543"/>{{rp|§7.4.12}} Deprecated by omission from later RFCs<ref name="RFC_3261"/> and by non-registration with the IANA.<ref name="IANA"/> ;{{anchor|412}} 412 Conditional Request Failed : The given precondition has not been met.<ref name="RFC_3903">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | title = Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Extension for Event State Publication | editor-last = Niemi | editor-first = Aki | month = October | year = 2004 | rfc = 3903 | sectionname = "412 Conditional Requset Failed" Response Code | section = 11.2.1 }}</ref> ;{{anchor|413}} 413 Request Entity Too Large : Request body too large.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.11}} ;{{anchor|414}} 414 Request-URI Too Long : The server is refusing to service the request because the Request-URI is longer than the server is willing to interpret.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.12}} ;{{anchor|415}} 415 Unsupported Media Type : Request body in a format not supported.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.13}} ;{{anchor|416}} 416 Unsupported URI Scheme : Request-URI is unknown to the server.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.14}} ;{{anchor|417}} 417 Unknown Resource-Priority : There was a resource-priority option tag, but no Resource-Priority header.<ref name="RFC_4412">{{cite IETF | title = Communications Resource Priority for the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) | rfc = 4412 | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | last1 = Schulzrinne | first1 = Henning | authorlink1 = Henning Schulzrinne | last2 = Polk | first2 = James | sectionname = No Known Namespace or Priority Value | section = 4.6.2 | year = 2006 | month = February }}</ref> ;{{anchor|420}} 420 Bad Extension : Bad SIP Protocol Extension used, not understood by the server.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.15}} ;{{anchor|421}} 421 Extension Required : The server needs a specific extension not listed in the Supported header.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.16}} ;{{anchor|422}} 422 Session Interval Too Small : The received request contains a Session-Expires header field with a duration below the minimum timer.<ref name="RFC_4028_sec_6">{{cite IETF | title = Session Timers in the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) | rfc = 4028 | sectionname = 422 Response Code Definition | section = 6 | last1 = Donovan | first1 = Steve | last2 = Rosenberg | first2 = Jonathan | year = 2005 | month = April | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] }}</ref> ;{{anchor|423}} 423 Interval Too Brief : Expiration time of the resource is too short.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.17}} ;{{anchor|424}} 424 Bad Location Information : The request's location content was malformed or otherwise unsatisfactory.<ref name="RFC_6422">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | title = Location Conveyance for the Session Initiation Protocol | rfc = 6442 | year = 2011 | month = December | last1 = Polk | first1 = James | last2 = Rosen | first2 = Brian | last3 = Peterson | first3 = Jon | sectionname = 424 (Bad Location Information) Response Code | section = 4.3 }}</ref> ;{{anchor|428}} 428 Use Identity Header : The server policy requires an Identity header, and one has not been provided.<ref name="RFC_4474">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | title = Enhancements for Authenticated Identity Management in the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) | rfc = 4474 | last1 = Peterson | first1 = Jon | last2 = Jennings | first2 = Cullen | year = 2006 | month = August }}</ref>{{rp|p11}} ;{{anchor|429}} 429 Provide Referrer Identity : The server did not receive a valid Referred-By token on the request.<ref name="RFC_3892">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | rfc = 3892 | last = Sparks | first = Robert J. | year = 2004 | month = September | title = The Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Referred-By Mechanism | sectionname = The 429 Provide Referrer Identity Error Response | section = 5 }}</ref> : A specific flow to a user agent has failed, although other flows may succeed. This response is intended for use between proxy devices, and should not be seen by an endpoint (and if it is seen by one, should be treated as a [[#400|400 Bad Request]] response).<ref name="RFC_5626">{{cite IETF | title = Managing Client-Initiated Connections in the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) | rfc = 5626 | year = 2009 | month = October | editor1-last = Jennings | editor1-first = Cullen | editor2-last = Mahy | editor2-first = Rohan | editor3-last = Audet | editor3-first = Francois | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] }}</ref>{{rp|§11.5}} ;{{anchor|433}} 433 Anonymity Disallowed : The request has been rejected because it was anonymous.<ref name="RFC_5079">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | rfc = 5079 | title = Rejecting Anonymous Requests in the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) | last = Rosenberg | first = Jonathan | year = 2007 | month = December | sectionname = 433 (Anonymity Disallowed) Definition | section = 5 }}</ref> ;{{anchor|436}} 436 Bad Identity-Info : The request has an Identity-Info header, and the URI scheme in that header cannot be dereferenced.<ref name="RFC_4474"/>{{rp|p11}} ;{{anchor|437}} 437 Unsupported Certificate : The server was unable to validate a certificate for the domain that signed the request.<ref name="RFC_4474"/>{{rp|p11}} ;{{anchor|438}} 438 Invalid Identity Header : The server obtained a valid certificate that the request claimed was used to sign the request, but was unable to verify that signature.<ref name="RFC_4474"/>{{rp|p12}} ;{{anchor|439}} 439 First Hop Lacks Outbound Support : The first outbound [[Session Initiation Protocol#Proxy server|proxy]] the user is attempting to register through does not support the "outbound" feature of RFC 5626, although the [[Session Initiation Protocol#Registrar|registrar]] does.<ref name="RFC_5626"/>{{rp|§11.6}} ;{{anchor|440}} 440 Max-Breadth Exceeded : If a SIP proxy determines a response context has insufficient Incoming Max-Breadth to carry out a desired parallel fork, and the proxy is unwilling/unable to compensate by forking serially or sending a redirect, that proxy MUST return a 440 response. A client receiving a 440 response can infer that its request did not reach all possible destinations. <ref name="RFC_5393">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | rfc = 5393 | title = Addressing an Amplification Vulnerability in Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Forking Proxies | year = 2008 | month = December }}</ref> ;{{anchor|469}} 469 Bad Info Package : If a SIP UA receives an INFO request associated with an Info Package that the UA has not indicated willingness to receive, the UA MUST send a 469 response, which contains a Recv-Info header field with Info Packages for which the UA is willing to receive INFO requests. <ref name="RFC_6086">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | rfc = 6086 | title = Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) INFO Method and Package Framework | year = 2011 | month = January }}</ref> ;{{anchor|470}} 470 Consent Needed : The source of the request did not have the permission of the recipient to make such a request.<ref name="RFC_5360">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | title = A Framework for Consent-Based Communications in the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) | rfc = 5360 | last1 = Rosenberg | first1 = Jonathan | last2 = Willis | first2 = Dean | editor-last = Camarillo | editor-first = Gonzalo | sectionname = Definition of the 470 Response Code | section = 5.9.2 | year = 2008 | month = October }}</ref> ;{{anchor|480}} 480 Temporarily Unavailable : Callee currently unavailable.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.18}} ;{{anchor|481}} 481 Call/Transaction Does Not Exist : Server received a request that does not match any dialog or transaction.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.19}} ;{{anchor|482}} 482 Loop Detected : Server has detected a loop.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.20}} ;{{anchor|483}} 483 Too Many Hops : Max-Forwards header has reached the value '0'.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.21}} ;{{anchor|484}} 484 Address Incomplete : Request-URI incomplete.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.22}} ;{{anchor|485}} 485 Ambiguous : Request-URI is ambiguous.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.23}} ;{{anchor|486}} 486 Busy Here : Callee is busy.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.24}} ;{{anchor|487}} 487 Request Terminated : Request has terminated by bye or cancel.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.25}} ;{{anchor|488}} 488 Not Acceptable Here : Some aspect of the session description or the Request-URI is not acceptable, or Codec issue.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.26}} ;{{anchor|489}} 489 Bad Event : The server did not understand an event package specified in an Event header field.<ref name="RFC_3265"/>{{rp|§7.3.2}}<ref name="RFC_6665"/>{{rp|§8.3.2}} ;{{anchor|491}} 491 Request Pending : Server has some pending request from the same dialog.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.27}} ;{{anchor|493}} 493 Undecipherable : Request contains an encrypted MIME body, which recipient can not decrypt.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.4.28}} ;{{anchor|494}} 494 Security Agreement Required : The server has received a request that requires a negotiated security mechanism, and the response contains a list of suitable security mechanisms for the requester to choose between,<ref name="RFC_3329">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | rfc = 3329 | year = 2003 | month = January | title = Security Mechanism Agreement for the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) | last1 = Arkko | first1 = Jari | last2 = Torvinen | first2 = Vesa | last3 = Camarillo | first3 = Gonzalo | last4 = Niemi | first4 = Aki | last5 = Haukka | first5 = Tao }}</ref>{{rp|§§2.3.1–2.3.2}} or a [[digest authentication]] challenge.<ref name="RFC_3329"/>{{rp|§2.4}}
== 5xx—Server Failure Responses == ;{{anchor|500}} 500 Server Internal Error : The server could not fulfill the request due to some unexpected condition.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.5.1}} ;{{anchor|501}} 501 Not Implemented : The server does not have the ability to fulfill the request, such as because it does not recognize the request method. (Compare with [[#405|405 Method Not Allowed]], where the server recognizes the method but does not allow or support it.)<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.5.2}} ;{{anchor|502}} 502 Bad Gateway : The server is acting as a [[Gateway (computer program)|gateway]] or [[Proxy server|proxy]], and received an invalid response from a downstream server while attempting to fulfill the request.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.5.3}} ;{{anchor|503}} 503 Service Unavailable : The server is undergoing maintenance or is temporarily overloaded and so cannot process the request. A "Retry-After" header field may specify when the client may reattempt its request.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.5.4}} ;{{anchor|504}} 504 Server Time-out : The server attempted to access another server in attempting to process the request, and did not receive a prompt response.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.5.5}} ;{{anchor|505}} 505 Version Not Supported : The SIP protocol version in the request is not supported by the server.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.5.6}} ;{{anchor|513}} 513 Message Too Large : The request message length is longer than the server can process.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.5.7}} ;{{anchor|580}} 580 Precondition Failure : The server is unable or unwilling to meet some constraints specified in the offer.<ref name="RFC_3312">{{cite IETF | title = Integration of Resource Management and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) | rfc = 3312 | sectionname = Refusing an offer | section = 8 | last = Rosenberg | first = Jonathan | editor1-last = Camarillo | editor1-first = Gonzalo | editor2-last = Marshall | editor2-first = Bill | year = 2002 | month = October | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] }}</ref>
== 6xx—Global Failure Responses == ;{{anchor|600}} 600 Busy Everywhere : All possible destinations are busy. Unlike the 486 response, this response indicates the destination knows there are no alternative destinations (such as a voicemail server) able to accept the call.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.6.1}} ;{{anchor|603}} 603 Decline : The destination does not wish to participate in the call, or cannot do so, and additionally the destination knows there are no alternative destinations (such as a voicemail server) willing to accept the call.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.6.2}} ;{{anchor|604}} 604 Does Not Exist Anywhere : The server has authoritative information that the requested user does not exist anywhere.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.6.3}} ;{{anchor|606}} 606 Not Acceptable : The user's agent was contacted successfully but some aspects of the session description such as the requested media, bandwidth, or addressing style were not acceptable.<ref name="RFC_3261"/>{{rp|§21.6.4}} ;{{anchor|607}} 607 Unwanted : The called party did not want this call from the calling party. Future attempts from the calling party are likely to be similarly rejected.<ref name="RFC_8197">{{cite IETF | publisher = [[Internet Engineering Task Force|IETF]] | rfc = 8197 | title = A SIP Response Code for Unwanted Calls | year = 2017 | month = July }}</ref>
