===Plasma physics=== {{See also|Plasma physics}}
*{{cite book |last=Langmuir |first=I. |author-link=Irving Langmuir |year=1961 |title=The Collected Works of Irving Langmuir Volume 3: Thermionic Phenomena: Papers from 1916–1937 |publisher=[[Pergamon Press]] }} *{{cite book |last=Langmuir |first=I. |author-link=Irving Langmuir |year=1961 |title=The Collected Works of Irving Langmuir Volume 4: Electrical Discharges: Papers from 1923–1931 |publisher=[[Pergamon Press]] }} :These two volumes from Nobel Prize winning scientist [[Irving Langmuir]], include his early published papers resulting from his experiments with ionized gases (i.e. [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]]). The books summarise many of the basic properties of plasmas. Langmuir coined the word ''plasma'' in about 1928. *{{cite book |last=Alfvén |first=H. |author1-link=Hannes Alfvén |last2=Fälthammar |first2=C.-G. |author2-link=Carl-Gunne Fälthammar |year=1963 |title=Cosmical Electrodynamics |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] }} :[[Hannes Alfvén]] won the Nobel Prize for his development of [[magnetohydrodynamics]] (MHD) the science that models plasma as fluids. This book lays down the ground work, but also shows that MHD may be inadequate for low-density plasmas such as space plasmas.
==Astronomy and astrophysics== *{{cite book |last=Kopernik |first=Mikolaj |author-link=Nicolaus Copernicus |title=De revolutionibus orbium coelestium |language=Latin |trans-title=On the Revolutions of the Heavenly Spheres |publisher=Johannes Petreius |location=Nuremberg |year=1543 |pages=405|title-link=De revolutionibus orbium coelestium }} : Favoured the heliocentric model (first advanced by [[Aristarchus of Samos|Aristarchus]]) over the [[Ptolemaic model]] of the solar system; sometimes credited with starting the [[Scientific Revolution]] in the Western world.
*{{cite book |last=Kepler |first=Johannes |author-link=Johannes Kepler |title=Astronomia nova |language=Latin |trans-title=New Astronomy |location=Prague |year=1609 |others=([http://www.library.usyd.edu.au/libraries/rare/modernity/kepler4.html Available online])|title-link=Astronomia nova }} :*{{cite book |last=Kepler |first=Johannes |author-mask=1 |title=New Astronomy |others=Translated by William H. Donahue |location=Cambridge |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=1992 |isbn=978-0-521-30131-2}} :Provided strong arguments for [[heliocentrism]] and contributed valuable insight into the movement of the planets, including the first mention of their elliptical path and the change of their movement to the movement of free floating bodies as opposed to objects on rotating spheres (two of [[Kepler's laws]]). One of the most important works of the [[Scientific Revolution]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Voelkel |first=James R. |title=The composition of Kepler's Astronomia nova |year=2001 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton |isbn=978-0-691-00738-0 |page=1}}</ref>
*{{cite book |last=Kepler |first=Johannes |title=Harmonices Mundi |language=Latin |trans-title=Harmony of the World |year=1619 |others=([http://posner.library.cmu.edu/Posner/books/pages.cgi?call=520_K38PI&layout=vol0/part0/copy0 Available online])|title-link=Harmonices Mundi }} :*{{cite book |others=Translated into English with an introduction and notes by E. J. Aiton, A. M. Duncan and J. V. Field |last=Kepler |first=Johannes |author-mask=1 |title=The harmony of the world |year=1997 |publisher=American Philosophical Society |location=Philadelphia |isbn=978-0-87169-209-2}} :Developed the third of [[Kepler's laws]].{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}
===Astrophysics=== {{See also|Astrophysics}} Astrophysics employs physical principles "to ascertain the nature of the [[astronomical object|heavenly bodies]], rather than their positions or motions in space."<ref>{{Citation | last = Keeler | first = James E. | author-link = James E. Keeler | title = The Importance of Astrophysical Research and the Relation of Astrophysics to the Other Physical Sciences | journal = The Astrophysical Journal | volume = 6 | issue = 4 | pages = 271–288 | date = November 1897 | bibcode = 1897ApJ.....6..271K |doi = 10.1086/140401}}</ref>
*{{cite journal |first=E. M. |last=Burbidge |first2=G. R. |last2=Burbidge, |first3=F. |last3=Fowler |author3-link=William Alfred Fowler |last4=Hoyle |author4-link=Fred Hoyle |year=1957 |title=Synthesis of the Elements in Stars |journal=[[Reviews of Modern Physics]] |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=547–650 |bibcode=1957RvMP...29..547B |doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.29.547 |first4=F.|title-link=Synthesis of the Elements in Stars }} :A landmark article of stellar physics, analysing several key processes that might be responsible for the synthesis of chemical elements in nature and their relative abundances; it is credited with originating what is now the theory of [[stellar nucleosynthesis]]. *{{cite journal |first=Sandra M. |last=Faber |author-link=Sandra M. Faber |first2=Robert |last2=Jackson |author2-link=Robert Jackson (scientist) |title=Velocity dispersions and mass-to-light ratios for elliptical galaxies |journal=[[Astrophysical Journal]] |volume=204 |issue=6 |page=668 |year=1976 |doi=10.1086/154215 |bibcode=1976ApJ...204..668F}} :Introduction of the [[Faber–Jackson relation|Faber–Jackson law]] relating galaxy luminosity and velocity dispersion.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} *{{cite journal |first=R. B |last=Tully |author-link=Brent Tully |first2=J. R. |last2=Fisher |title=A new method of determining distances to galaxies |journal=[[Astronomy and Astrophysics]] |volume=54 |issue=3 |pages=661&ndash;673 |year=1977 |bibcode=1977A&A....54..661T }} :Introduction of the [[Tully–Fisher relation]] between galaxy luminosity and rotation-curve amplitude.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} *{{cite journal |first=Laura |last=Ferrarese |first2=David |author2-link=David Merritt |title=A fundamental relation between supermassive black holes and their host galaxies |journal=[[Astrophysical Journal Letters]] |volume=539 |issue=1 |pages=L9&ndash;L12 |year=2000 |doi=10.1086/312838 |bibcode=2000ApJ...539L...9F |arxiv=astro-ph/0006053 |last2=Merritt }} : Introduction of the [[M-sigma relation]] between black hole mass and galaxy velocity dispersion.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}
===Cosmology=== {{See also|Physical cosmology}}
*{{cite journal |last=Sakharov |first=A. D. |title=Violation of CP invariance, C asymmetry, and baryon asymmetry of the universe |journal=Journal of Experimental and Theoretical Physics |year=1967 |volume=5 |pages=24–27 |doi=10.1070/PU1991v034n05ABEH002497 |bibcode=1991SvPhU..34..392S |issue=5}} :Introduced the conditions necessary for [[baryogenesis]], by making use of recent results (discovery of [[CP violation]], etc). Republished in 1991 in Soviet Physics Uspekhi, vol.34 (number 5), pages 392-393.
*{{cite book |first1=Edward |last1=Kolb |author1-link=Edward Kolb |first2=Michael |last2=Turner |author2-link=Michael Turner (cosmologist) |title=The Early Universe |publisher=Addison–Wesley |year=1988 |isbn=978-0-201-11604-5}} :Reference textbook on cosmology, discussing both observational and theoretical issues.
* {{cite journal |title=A Preliminary Measurement of the Cosmic Microwave Background Spectrum by the Cosmic Background Explorer (COBE) Satellite |author1=J. C. Mather |author2=E. S. Cheng |author3=R.E. Eplee, Jr. |author4=R. B. Isaacman |author5=S. S. Meyer |author6=R. A. Shafer |author7=R. Weiss |author8=E. L. Wright |author9=C. L. Bennett |author10=N. W. Boggess |author11=E. Dwek |author12=S. Gulkis |author13=M. G. Hauser |author14=M. Janssen |author15=T. Kelsall |author16=P. M. Lubin |author17=S. H. Moseley, Jr. |author18=T. L. Murdock |author19=R. F. Silverberg |author20=G. F. Smoot |author21=D. T. Wilkinson |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=354 |pages=L37–40 |year=1990 |doi=10.1086/185717 |bibcode=1990ApJ...354L..37M}} *{{cite journal |last=Mather |first=J. C. |author2=Fixsen, D. J. |author3=Shafer, R. A. |author4=Mosier, C. |author5=Wilkinson, D. T. |title=Calibrator Design for the Far-Infrared Absolute Spectrophotometer (FIRAS) |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |date=20 February 1999 |volume=512 |issue=2 |pages=511–520 |doi=10.1086/306805 |bibcode=1999ApJ...512..511M |arxiv=astro-ph/9810373 }} :Reported results from the [[Cosmic Background Explorer|COBE]] satellite, which was developed by NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center to measure the diffuse infrared and microwave radiation from the early universe to the limits set by our astrophysical environment. Measurements by a Far Infrared Absolute Spectrophotometer (FIRAS) confirmed that the [[cosmic microwave background]] (CMB) spectrum is that of a nearly perfect [[black body]] with a temperature of 2.725&nbsp;±&nbsp;0.002&nbsp;K. This observation matches the predictions of the hot [[Big Bang]] theory extraordinarily well, and indicates that nearly all of the radiant energy of the Universe was released within the first year after the Big Bang. The first paper presents initial results; the second, final results.
* {{cite journal |title=Structure in the COBE differential microwave radiometer first-year maps |author=G. F. Smoot |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=396 |pages=L1–5 |year=1992 |bibcode=1992ApJ...396L...1S |doi=10.1086/186504 |display-authors=1 |last2=Bennett |first2=C. L. |last3=Kogut |first3=A. |last4=Wright |first4=E. L. |last5=Aymon |first5=J. |last6=Boggess |first6=N. W. |last7=Cheng |first7=E. S. |last8=De Amici |first8=G. |last9=Gulkis |first9=S. |last10=Hauser |first10=M. G. |last11=Hinshaw |first11=G. |last12=Jackson |first12=P. D. |last13=Janssen |first13=M. |last14=Kaita |first14=E. |last15=Kelsall |first15=T. |last16=Keegstra |first16=P. |last17=Lineweaver |first17=C. |last18=Loewenstein |first18=K. |last19=Lubin |first19=P. |last20=Mather |first20=J. |last21=Meyer |first21=S. S. |last22=Moseley |first22=S. H. |last23=Murdock |first23=T. |last24=Rokke |first24=L. |last25=Silverberg |first25=R. F. |last26=Tenorio |first26=L. |last27=Weiss |first27=R. |last28=Wilkinson |first28=D. T.}} *{{cite journal |last=Bennett |first=C. L. |author2=Banday, A. J. |author3=Górski, K. M. |author4=Hinshaw, G. |author5=Jackson, P. |author6=Keegstra, P. |author7=Kogut, A. |author8=Smoot, G. F. |author9=Wilkinson, D. T. |author10=Wright, E. L. |title=Four-Year ''COBE'' DMR Cosmic Microwave Background Observations: Maps and Basic Results |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |year=1996 |volume=464 |issue=1 |pages=L1–L4 |doi=10.1086/310075 |bibcode=1996ApJ...464L...1B |arxiv=astro-ph/9601067 }} :Presents results from the Differential Microwave Radiometer (DMR) on the [[Cosmic Background Explorer|COBE]] satellite. This maps the cosmic radiation and searches for variations in brightness. The CMB was found to have intrinsic "anisotropy" for the first time, at a level of a part in 100,000. These tiny variations in the intensity of the CMB over the sky show how matter and energy was distributed when the Universe was still very young. Later, through a process still poorly understood, the early structures seen by DMR developed into galaxies, galaxy clusters, and the large scale structure that we see in the Universe today. The first paper presents initial results; the second, final results.
* {{cite journal |title=The COBE Diffuse Infrared Background Experiment Search for the Cosmic Infrared Background. I. Limits and Detections |author=Hauser |journal=The Astrophysical Journal |volume=508 |issue=1 |pages=25–43 |year=1998 |url=http://www.iop.org/EJ/article/0004-637X/508/1/25/37784.pdf |doi=10.1086/306379 |last2=Arendt |first2=R. G. |last3=Kelsall |first3=T. |last4=Dwek |first4=E. |last5=Odegard |first5=N. |last6=Weiland |first6=J. L. |last7=Freudenreich |first7=H. T. |last8=Reach |first8=W. T. |last9=Silverberg |first9=R. F. |last10=Moseley |bibcode=1998ApJ...508...25H |arxiv=astro-ph/9806167 |display-authors=1 |first10=S. H. |last11=Pei |first11=Y. C. |last12=Lubin |first12=P. |last13=Mather |first13=J. C. |last14=Shafer |first14=R. A. |last15=Smoot |first15=G. F. |last16=Weiss |first16=R. |last17=Wilkinson |first17=D. T. |last18=Wright |first18=E. L. }} :Presents results from the Diffuse Infrared Background Experiment (DIRBE) on the [[Cosmic Background Explorer|COBE]] satellite. This searches for the cosmic infrared background radiation produced by the first galaxies. Infrared absolute sky brightness maps in the wavelength range 1.25 to 240 micrometres were obtained to carry out a search for the cosmic infrared background (CIB). The CIB was originally detected in the two longest DIRBE wavelength bands, 140 and 240 micrometres, and in the short-wavelength end of the FIRAS spectrum. Subsequent analyses have yielded detections of the CIB in the near-infrared DIRBE sky maps. The CIB represents a "core sample" of the Universe; it contains the cumulative emissions of stars and galaxies dating back to the epoch when these objects first began to form.
==Atomic and molecular physics== {{main|Atomic physics| Molecular physics|Atomic, molecular, and optical physics}}{{See also|Timeline of atomic and subatomic physics}} *{{cite book |last=Van der Waals |first=Johannes Diderik |author-link=Johannes Diderik van der Waals |title=Over de Continuiteit van den Gas- en Vloeistoftoestand |language=Dutch |trans-title=''On the continuity of the gas and liquid state'' |year=1873 |publisher=A.W. Sijthoff |location=Leiden |isbn=978-0-486-49593-4 |url=http://ilorentz.org/history/proefschriften/sources/vanderWaals_1873.pdf}} :James Clerk Maxwell reviewed this work in ''Nature'' and concluded that "there can be no doubt that the name of Van der Waals will soon be among the foremost in molecular science." Johannes Diderik van der Waals received the Nobel Prize in 1910 for his work on the equation of state for gases and liquids. * {{Cite journal |language=German |title=Über eine neue Art von Strahlen |journal=Sitzungsberichte der Würzburger Physik-medic. Gesellschaft |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=153–157 |date=28 December 1895 |url=http://www.mindfully.org/Nucs/Roetgen-X-Rays28dec1895.htm |accessdate=24 Aug 2013 |last=Röntgen |first=W.C. |trans-title=On A New Kind Of Rays |doi=10.3322/canjclin.22.3.153 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105181651/http://www.mindfully.org/Nucs/Roetgen-X-Rays28dec1895.htm |archivedate=5 November 2010 |df= }} :Discovery of X-rays, leading to the very first Nobel Prize in Physics for the author. * {{cite journal | last1 = Thomson | first1 = J.J. | year = 1897 | title = Cathode rays | url = http://web.lemoyne.edu/~GIUNTA/thomson1897.html | journal = Philosophical Magazine | volume = 44 | issue = 269| pages = 293–316 | doi=10.1080/14786449708621070}} : The classic experimental measurement of the mass and charge of cathode ray "corpuscles", later called electrons. Won the Nobel Physics Prize (in 1906) for this discovery.
*Zeeman (1897) papers ** {{Cite journal |first=P. |last=Zeeman |title=On the influence of Magnetism on the Nature of the Light emitted by a Substance |journal=Phil. Mag. |volume=43 |pages=226 |year=1897}} ** {{Cite journal |first=P. |last=Zeeman |title=Doubles and triplets in the spectrum produced by external magnetic forces |journal=Phil. Mag. |volume=44 |issue=266 |pages=55–60 |year=1897 |doi=10.1080/14786449708621028}} ** {{Cite journal |first=P. |last=Zeeman |title=The Effect of Magnetisation on the Nature of Light Emitted by a Substance |journal=Nature |volume=55 |date=11 February 1897 |pages=347 |doi=10.1038/055347a0 |issue=1424 |bibcode=1897Natur..55..347Z }} : Described the [[Zeeman effect|famous effect]] of splitting of spectral lines in magnetic fields; earned author a Nobel Physics prize citation (1902).
* Planck, Max (1901). : See [[#quantum mechanics|quantum mechanics]] section. * Einstein, Albert (1905). : See [[#quantum mechanics|quantum mechanics]] section. * Bohr, Niels (1913-4). : See [[#quantum mechanics|quantum mechanics]] section. * {{Cite journal |title=The High Frequency Spectra of the Elements |url=http://www.chemistry.co.nz/henry_moseley.htm |author1=H. G. J. Moseley |author2=M. A. |journal=Phil. Mag. |year=1913 |pages=1024–1034 |doi=10.1080/14786441308635052 |volume=26 |issue=156 |access-date=2013-08-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710155838/http://www.chemistry.co.nz/henry_moseley.htm |archive-date=2013-07-10 |dead-url=yes |df= }} : This [[Moseley's law|announced a law]] that gave decisive evidence for [[atomic number]] from studies of X-ray spectra, which could be explained by the Bohr model. * {{cite journal | last1 = Stark | first1 = J. | year = 1914 | title = Beobachtungen über den Effekt des elektrischen Feldes auf Spektrallinien I. Quereffekt |language= German |trans-title=Observations of the effect of the electric field on spectral lines I. Transverse effect | doi = 10.1002/andp.19143480702 | journal = Annalen der Physik | volume = 43 | issue = 7| pages = 965–983 |bibcode = 1914AnP...348..965S }} Published earlier (1913) in Sitzungsberichten der Kgl. Preuss. Akad. d. Wiss. : Described the [[Stark effect|famous effect]] of splitting of spectral lines in electric fields (c.f. [[Zeeman effect]]) as predicted by Voigt.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Voigt | first1 = Waldemar | year = 1901 | title = Ueber das Elektrische Analogon des Zeemaneffectes (On the electric analogue of the Zeeman effect) | doi = 10.1002/andp.19013090112 | journal = Annalen der Physik | volume = 4 | issue = 1| pages = 197–208 |bibcode = 1901AnP...309..197V }}</ref> Observed the same year (1913) as Lo Surdo;<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Leone | first1 = M. | last2 = Paoletti | first2 = A. | last3 = Robotti | first3 = N. | year = 2004 | title = A Simultaneous Discovery: The Case of Johannes Stark and Antonino Lo Surdo | url = | journal = Physics in Perspective | volume = 6 | issue = 3| pages = 271–294 | doi=10.1007/s00016-003-0170-2|bibcode = 2004PhP.....6..271L }}</ref> the work won a Nobel Physics prize for Stark.
*{{cite journal |author=Einstein, A. |author1-link=Albert Einstein |title=Strahlungs-Emission und -Absorption nach der Quantentheorie |trans-title=Radiation Emission and Absorption according to the Quantum theory |language=German |journal=Verhandlungen der Deutschen Physikalischen Gesellschaft |volume=18 |pages=318–323 |year=1916 |bibcode=1916DPhyG..18..318E }} **{{cite journal |author=Einstein, A. |author1-link=Albert Einstein |author-mask=2 |year=1916 |title=Zur Quantentheorie der Strahlung |trans-title=On the Quantum Theory of Radiation |journal=[[Mitteilungen der Physikalischen Gessellschaft Zürich]] |language=German |volume=18 |pages=47–62 |ref=harv}} **{{cite journal |author=Einstein, A. |author1-link=Albert Einstein |author-mask=2 |title=Zur Quantentheorie der Strahlung |trans-title=On the Quantum Theory of Radiation |language=German |year=1917 |journal=[[Physikalische Zeitschrift]] |volume=18 |pages=121–128 |bibcode=1917PhyZ...18..121E |ref=harv }} ***Translated in {{cite book |last1=ter Haar |first1=D. |author-link=Dirk ter Haar |year=1967 |pages=167–183 |title=The Old Quantum Theory |publisher=[[Pergamon]] |lccn=66029628 |ref=harv }} Also in [http://astro1.panet.utoledo.edu/~ljc/einstein_ab.pdf Boorse, H.A., Motz, L. (1966). ''The world of the atom'', edited with commentaries, Basic Books, Inc., New York, pp. 888–901.] : Formulated the concepts of [[spontaneous emission|spontaneous]] and [[stimulated emission]].
* Arnold Sommerfeld (1919). : See [[#quantum mechanics|quantum mechanics]] section.
* {{Cite journal |author=Auger, P.V. |url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k3130n.image.f187.langFR |title=Sur les rayons &beta; secondaires produits dans un gaz par des rayons X |trans-title=On the secondary &beta;-rays produced in a gas by X-rays |journal=C. R. Acad. Sci.|volume=177 |year=1923 |pages=169–171}} :Description on an [[Auger effect|atomic ionization effect]] first discovered by Meitner,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF01326962 |author=L. Meitner |title=Über die Entstehung der &beta;-Strahl-Spektren radioaktiver Substanzen |journal=Z. Phys. |volume=9 |issue=1 |year=1922 |pages=131–144 |bibcode=1922ZPhy....9..131M }}</ref> but named for the later discoverer, Auger. * de Broglie, Louis (1924). : See [[#quantum mechanics|quantum mechanics]] section. * Matrix mechanics papers: W. Heisenberg (1925), M. Born and P. Jordan (1925), M. Born, W. Heisenberg, and P. Jordan (1926). : See [[#quantum mechanics|quantum mechanics]] section. * Schroedinger, E (1926). : See [[#quantum mechanics|quantum mechanics]] section. * {{cite journal |last=Raman |first=C. V. |title=A new radiation |journal=Indian J. Phys. |year=1928 |volume=2 |pages=387–398 |hdl=10821/377}} :Relates the experimental discovery of the [[Raman effect|inelastic scattering of light]] (predicted theoretically by [[Adolf Smekal|A. Smekal]] in 1923<ref name=smekal>{{Cite journal| first1 = A. | title = Zur Quantentheorie der Dispersion | journal = Naturwissenschaften| last1 = Smekal | volume = 11| issue = 43 | pages = 873–875 | year = 1923 | doi = 10.1007/BF01576902|bibcode = 1923NW.....11..873S }}</ref>) in liquids (with [[Kariamanickam Srinivasa Krishnan|K. S. Krishnan]]), for which Raman receives the [[Nobel Prize]] in Physics in 1930.<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = R. | title = C. V. Raman and the Discovery of the Raman Effect | journal = Physics in Perspective| last1 = Singh | volume = 4| issue = 4 | pages = 399–420 | year = 2002 | doi = 10.1007/s000160200002|bibcode = 2002PhP.....4..399S }}</ref> Observed independently soon after (in crystals) by [[Grigory Landsberg|G. Landsberg]] and [[Leonid Isaakovich Mandelshtam|L. I. Mandelstam]].<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = G.| last2 = Mandelstam| first2 = L.| last1 = Landsberg | title = Eine neue Erscheinung bei der Lichtzerstreuung in Krystallen | journal = Naturwissenschaften | volume = 16| issue = 28 | pages = 557–558 | year = 1928| doi = 10.1007/BF01506807|bibcode = 1928NW.....16..557. }}</ref>
==Classical mechanics== {{See also|Classical mechanics|History of classical mechanics}} ''[[Classical mechanics]]'' is the system of physics begun by Isaac Newton and his contemporaries. It is concerned with the motion of [[macroscopic]] objects at speeds well below the [[speed of light]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Dugas |first=René |title=A history of mechanics |year=1988 |publisher=Dover Publications |location=New York |isbn=978-0-486-65632-8 |edition=Dover |others=Foreword by Louis de Broglie ; translated into English by J.R. Maddox}}</ref> *{{cite book |last=Galilei |first=Galileo |author-link=Galileo Galilei |year=1638 |title=Discorsi e dimostrazioni matematiche, intorno à due nuove scienze attenenti alla mecanica & i movimenti locali |language=Latin |trans-title=[[Two New Sciences]] |location=[[Leiden]] |publisher=[[House of Elzevir|Louis Elsevier]]}} :*Classic (first and original<ref>{{cite news |title=The foundation of mechanics |url=https://archive.org/stream/independen79v80newy#page/n38/mode/1up |newspaper=The Independent |date=July 6, 1914 |accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref>) English translation: {{cite book |last=Galilei |first=Galileo |author-mask=1 |title=Mathematical discourses and demonstrations, relating to Two New Sciences |others=Translation by Henry Crew and Alfonso de Salvio |year=1914}} :*Recent English translation: {{cite book |last=Galilei |first=Galileo |author-mask=1 |others=Translated and compiled by Stillman Drake |title=Two New sciences, including Centers of gravity & Force of percussion |year=1974 |publisher=Wisconsin University Press |location=Madison |isbn=978-0-299-06404-4}}
*{{cite book |last=Descartes |first=René |author-link=René Descartes |title=Principia philosophiae |language=Latin |trans-title=[[Principles of Philosophy]] |year=1983 |publisher=Reidel |location=Dordrecht |isbn=978-90-277-1451-0 |edition=Reprint |others=Translation with explanatory notes by Valentine Rodger Miller and Reese P. Miller |origyear=1644, with additional material from the French translation of 1647}} *{{cite book |first=Isaac |last=Newton |author-link=Isaac Newton |title=Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica |language=Latin |trans-title=Mathematical principles of natural philosophy |year=1687|title-link=Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica }} :A three-volume work, often called ''Principia'' or ''Principia Mathematica''. One of the most influential scientific books ever published, it contains the statement of [[Newton's laws of motion]] forming the foundation of [[classical mechanics]] as well as his [[Gravity|law of universal gravitation]]. He derives [[laws of Kepler|Kepler's laws]] for the motion of the [[planet]]s (which were first obtained empirically).{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}
*{{cite book |first=Joseph Louis |last=Lagrange |author-link=Joseph Louis Lagrange |title=Mécanique Analytique |language=French |trans-title=Analytical mechanics |year=1788|title-link=Joseph Louis Lagrange#Mécanique analytique }} : Lagrange's masterpiece on mechanics and hydrodynamics. Based largely on the [[calculus of variations]], this work introduced [[Lagrangian mechanics]] including the notion of [[virtual work]], [[generalized coordinates]], and the [[Lagrangian mechanics|Lagrangian]]. Lagrange also further developed the [[principle of least action]] and introduced the [[Lagrangian and Eulerian coordinates|Lagrangian reference frame]] for fluid flow.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}
*Hamilton's papers. **{{Cite journal |first=William Rowan |last=Hamilton |author-link=William Rowan Hamilton |title=On the Application to Dynamics of a General Mathematical Method previously applied to Optics |journal=British Association Report 1834, Published 1835 |year=1835 |pages=513–518 |accessdate=14 Dec 2012 |url=http://www.maths.soton.ac.uk/EMIS/classics/Hamilton/BARep34A.pdf}} **{{Cite journal |first=William Rowan |last=Hamilton |author-link=William Rowan Hamilton |author-mask=1 |title=On a General Method in Dynamics; by which the Study of the Motions of all free Systems of attracting or repelling Points is reduced to the Search and Differentiation of one central Relation, or characteristic Function |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society |year=1835 |pages=247–308 |accessdate=14 Dec 2012 |url=http://www.maths.soton.ac.uk/EMIS/classics/Hamilton/GenMeth.pdf|doi=10.1098/rstl.1834.0017 |volume=124}} **{{Cite journal |first=William Rowan |last=Hamilton |author-link=William Rowan Hamilton |author-mask=1 |title=Second Essay on a General Method in Dynamics |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society |year=1835 |pages=95–144 |doi=10.1098/rstl.1835.0009 |accessdate=14 Dec 2012 |url=http://www.maths.soton.ac.uk/EMIS/classics/Hamilton/SecEssay.pdf |volume=125}} :These three papers used [[Hamiltonian optics|Hamilton's methods in optics]] to formulate mechanics anew; now called [[Hamiltonian mechanics]].
*Noether, Emmy (1918). : See [[#Mathematical physics|mathematical physics]] section.
* Kolmogorov-Arnol'd-Moser papers. ** Kolmogorov, A. N. "On Conservation of Conditionally Periodic Motions for a Small Change in Hamilton's Function." Dokl. Akad. Nauk SSSR 98, 527-530, 1954. **Moser, J. "On Invariant Curves of Area-Preserving Mappings of an Annulus." Nachr. Akad. Wiss. Göttingen Math.-Phys. Kl. II, 1-20, 1962. ** Arnol'd, V. I. "Proof of a Theorem of A. N. Kolmogorov on the Preservation of Conditionally Periodic Motions under a Small Perturbation of the Hamiltonian." Uspekhi Mat. Nauk 18, 13-40, 1963. : Set of important results in dynamical systems theory of [[Hamiltonian system]]s, named the [[KAM theorem]] after the authors' initials. Regarded in retrospect as a sign of chaos theory.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}
*{{cite book |first=Herbert |last=Goldstein |author-link=Herbert Goldstein |title=Classical Mechanics|title-link=Classical Mechanics (book) }} :A standard graduate textbook on classical mechanics, considered a good book on the subject.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}
===Fluid dynamics=== {{See also|Fluid dynamics|History of fluid mechanics}}
* [[Archimedes]] (ca. 250 BCE). "[[On Floating Bodies]]" (in ancient Greek, later tr. medieval Latin). Syracuse, Sicily. '''Partial preservation'''. : Two-book treatise regarded as the founding text of fluid mechanics and hydrostatics in particular. Contains an introduction of [[Archimedes principle|his famous principle]].<ref name="britannica.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/32808/Archimedes |title=Archimedes (Greek mathematician) - Britannica Online Encyclopedia |publisher=Britannica.com |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>
* [[Daniel Bernoulli]] (1738). ''Hydrodynamica, sive de viribus et motibus fluidorum commentarii'' (in Latin). Strasbourg. English translation: ''Hydrodynamics and Hydraulics'' by Daniel Bernoulli and [[Johann Bernoulli]] (Dover Publications, 1968). : Established a unified approach to hydrostatics and hydraulics; study of efflux; [[Bernoulli's Principle]].
* [[Jean le Rond D'Alembert]] (1752). ''Essai d'une nouvelle théorie de la résistance des fluides'' (in French) [Essay of a new theory of resistance of fluids]. Paris. : Introduces [[D'Alembert's Paradox]].
* {{cite journal |title=Principes généraux du mouvement des fluides |trans-title=General principles of fluid motion |first=Leonhard |last=Euler |author-link=Leonhard Euler |journal=Mémoires de l'Académie des Sciences de Berlin |year=1757 |volume=11 |pages=274&ndash;315}} (Presented in 1755) : Formulates the theory of fluid dynamics in terms of a set of partial differential equations: [[Euler equations (fluid dynamics)]]
* {{cite journal |title=Mémoire sur les lois du mouvement des fluides |first=Claude Louis |last=Navier |author-link=Claude-Louis Navier |journal=Mémoires de l'Académie des Sciences de l'Institut de France |volume=6 |pages=389&ndash;440 |year=1827}} (Presented in 1822) : First formulation of the [[Navier–Stokes equations]], albeit based on an incorrect molecular theory.
* {{cite journal |title=On the theory of the internal friction of fluids in motion, and of the equilibrium and motion of elastic solids |first=George Gabriel |last=Stokes |author-link=George Gabriel Stokes |journal=Transactions of the Cambridge Philosophical Society |volume=8 |pages=287 |year=1849}} (Presented in 1845) : Correct formulation of the [[Navier–Stokes equations]].
* {{cite journal |title=Über integrale der hydrodynamischen gleichungen, welche den wirbelbewegungen entsprechen |first=Hermann |last=von Helmholtz |author-link=Hermann von Helmholtz |journal=Journal für die Reine und Angewandte Mathematik |volume=55 |issue=55 |pages=25&ndash;55 |year=1858 |doi=10.1515/crll.1858.55.25}} : Introduced the study of vortex dynamics (see [[Vorticity]]).
*{{cite journal |title=An experimental investigation of the circumstances which determine whether the motion of water shall be direct or sinuous, and of the law of resistance in parallel channels |first=Osbourne |last=Reynolds |author-link=Osbourne Reynolds |journal=[[Philosophical Transactions]] |volume=174 |pages=935&ndash;982 |year=1883 |bibcode=1883RSPT..174..935R |doi=10.1098/rstl.1883.0029 }} :Introduces the dimensionless [[Reynolds number]], investigating the critical Reynolds number for transition from laminar to turbulent flow.
* {{cite journal |title=Über Flüssigkeitsbewegung bei sehr kleiner Reibung |first=Ludwig |last=Prandtl |author-link=Ludwig Prandtl |journal=Verhandlungen des Dritten Internationalen Mathematiker-Kongresses in Heidelberg 1904 |pages=484–491 |year=1905}} (Presented in 1904) : Introduces the [[Boundary layer]].
*{{cite journal |last=Kolmogorov |first=Andrey Nikolaevich |authorlink=Andrey Nikolaevich Kolmogorov |year=1941 |script-title=ru:Локальная структура турбулентности в несжимаемой жидкости при очень больших числах Рейнольдса |language=Russian |journal=[[Doklady Akademii Nauk SSSR]] |volume=30 |pages=299–303 |bibcode=1991RSPSA.434....9K |doi=10.1098/rspa.1991.0075 |issue=1890|title=The Local Structure of Turbulence in Incompressible Viscous Fluid for Very Large Reynolds Numbers }}. Translated into English by {{cite journal |last=Kolmogorov |first=Andrey Nikolaevich |date=July 8, 1991 |title=The local structure of turbulence in incompressible viscous fluid for very large Reynolds numbers |journal=[[Proceedings of the Royal Society A]] |volume=434 |issue=1991 |pages=9–13 |doi=10.1098/rspa.1991.0075 |bibcode=1991RSPSA.434....9K }} :Introduces a quantitative theory of turbulence.
==Computational physics== * S. Ulam, R. D. Richtmyer, and J. von Neumann (1947). [http://library.lanl.gov/cgi-bin/getfile?00329286.pdf "Statistical methods in neutron diffusion"]; LANL Scientific Laboratory report LAMS–551. Retrieved 2011-10-23. :This paper records the first use of the [[Monte Carlo method]], created at [[LANL|Los Alamos]]. * Metropolis, N.; et al. (1953) : See [[#Statistical mechanics and Thermodynamics|statistical mechanics and thermodynamics]] section . * Fermi, E.; Pasta, J.; Ulam, S. (1955) : [http://www.osti.gov/accomplishments/documents/fullText/ACC0041.pdf "Studies of Nonlinear Problems" (accessed 25 Sep 2012)]. Los Alamos Laboratory Document LA-1940. :The [[Fermi–Pasta–Ulam–Tsingou problem|Fermi-Ulam-Pasta-Tsingou simulation]] was an important early demonstration of the ability of computers to deal with nonlinear (physics) problems and its surprising result regarding [[equipartition theorem|thermal equipartition]] hinted towards [[chaos theory]].
*Molecular dynamics. **{{cite journal |first=B. J. |last=Alder |authorlink= |author2=T. E. Wainwright |year=1959 |title=Studies in Molecular Dynamics. I. General Method |journal=J. Chem. Phys. |volume=31 |issue=2 |pages=459 |doi=10.1063/1.1730376 |bibcode=1959JChPh..31..459A }} **{{cite journal |journal=Phys Rev |volume=136 |author=[[Aneesur Rahman|A. Rahman]] |title=Correlations in the Motion of Atoms in Liquid Argon |issue=2A |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.136.A405 |year=1964 |page=A405–A411 |bibcode=1964PhRv..136..405R }} : Independent formulations of the method of [[molecular dynamics]].
==Condensed matter physics== {{See also|Condensed matter physics}} ''[[Condensed matter physics]]'' deals with the physical properties of condensed [[Phase (matter)|phases of matter]]. These properties appear when atoms interact strongly and adhere to each other or are otherwise concentrated. *Kamerlingh Onnes, H., "Further experiments with liquid helium. C. On the change of electric resistance of pure metals at very low temperatures, etc. IV. The resistance of pure mercury at helium temperatures." Comm. Phys. Lab. Univ. Leiden; No. 120b, 1911. *Kamerlingh Onnes, H., "Further experiments with liquid helium. D. On the change of electric resistance of pure metals at very low temperatures, etc. V. The disappearance of the resistance of mercury." Comm. Phys. Lab. Univ. Leiden; No. 122b, 1911. *Kamerlingh Onnes, H., "Further experiments with liquid helium. G. On the electrical resistance of pure metals, etc. VI. On the sudden change in the rate at which the resistance of mercury disappears." Comm. Phys. Lab. Univ. Leiden; No. 124c, 1911. :Series of articles about superconductivity. *{{cite book | last = Sommerfeld | first = Arnold | title = Elektronentheorie der Metalle | publisher = Springer Verlag | location = Berlin Heidelberg | year = 1933 | isbn = 978-3642950025 |pages=|first2=Hans|last2=Bethe|author-link=Arnold Sommerfeld|author-link2=Hans Bethe}} * [[John Bardeen|J. Bardeen]], [[Leon Neil Cooper|L. N. Cooper]], and [[John Robert Schrieffer|J. R. Schrieffer]] papers **{{cite journal |first=L. N. |last=Cooper |author-link=Leon Neil Cooper |title=Bound Electron Pairs in a Degenerate Fermi Gas |journal=[[Physical Review]] |volume=104 |pages=1189&ndash;1190 |year=1956 |bibcode=1956PhRv..104.1189C |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.104.1189 |issue=4 }} **{{cite journal |first=J. |last=Bardeen |author-link=John Bardeen |first2=L. N. |last2=Cooper |author2-link=Leon Neil Cooper |first3=J. R. |last3=Schrieffer |author3-link=John Robert Schrieffer |title=Microscopic Theory of Superconductivity |journal=[[Physical Review]] |volume=106 |issue=1 |pages=162&ndash;164 |year=1957 |bibcode=1957PhRv..106..162B |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.106.162 }} **{{cite journal |first=J. |last=Bardeen |author-link=John Bardeen |first2=L. N. |last2=Cooper |author2-link=Leon Neil Cooper |first3=J. R. |last3=Schrieffer |author3-link=John Robert Schrieffer |title=Theory of Superconductivity |journal=[[Physical Review]] |volume=108 |pages=1175–1204 |year=1957 |bibcode=1957PhRv..108.1175B |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.108.1175 |issue=5 }} :These three papers develop the [[BCS theory]] of usual (not high {{math|''T''<sub>C</sub>}}) superconductivity, relating the interaction of electrons and the [[phonons]] of a lattice. The authors were awarded the [[Nobel prize]] for this work.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}
