===Polymer physics=== {{See also|Polymer physics}}
*{{cite journal |last=Guth |first=Eugen |author-link=Eugene Guth |first2=Mark |last2=Hermann |author2-link=Herman Mark |title=Zur innermolekularen, Statistik, insbesondere bei Kettenmolekiilen I |language=German |trans-title=For the intra-molecular, statistics, especially for chain molecules I |journal=Monatshefte für Chemie |year=1934 |volume=65 |issue=1 |pages=93–121 |doi=10.1007/BF01522052}} :Contains the foundation of the ''kinetic theory of rubber elasticity'', including the first theoretical description of statistical mechanics of polymers with application to viscosity and rubber elasticity, and an expression for the entropy gain during the coiling of linear flexible molecules.
*{{cite journal |last=Guth |first=Eugene |author2=James, Hubert M. |title=Elastic and Thermoelastic Properties of Rubber like Materials |journal=Industrial & Engineering Chemistry |year=1941 |volume=33 |issue=5 |pages=624–629 |doi=10.1021/ie50377a017}} :Presented earlier by Guth at the American Chemical Society meeting of 1939, this article contains the first outline of the ''network'' theory of rubber elasticity. The resulting Guth-James equation of state is analogous to van der Waal's equation.
*{{cite journal |last=James |first=Hubert M. |author2=Guth, Eugene |title=Theory of the Elastic Properties of Rubber |journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics |year=1943 |volume=11 |issue=10 |page=455 |doi=10.1063/1.1723785 |bibcode=1943JChPh..11..455J }} :Presents a more detailed version of the network theory of rubber elasticity. The paper used average forces to some extent instead of thermodynamical functions. In statistical thermodynamics, these two procedures are equivalent. After some controversy within the literature, the James-Guth network theory is now generally accepted for larger extensions. See, e.g., Paul Flory's comments in ''Proc. Royal Soc. A.'' 351, 351 (1976).
*{{cite book |last=Flory |first=Paul J. |title=Principles of polymer chemistry |year=1992 |publisher=Cornell Univ. Press |location=Ithaca |isbn=978-0-8014-0134-3 |edition=15. pr.}} *{{cite book |last=Flory |first=Paul J. |title=Statistical mechanics of chain molecules |year=1969 |publisher=Interscience Publishers |location=New York |isbn=978-0-470-26495-9}} :*Reissued: {{cite book |last=Flory |first=Paul J. |author2=J. G. Jackson |author3=C. J. Wood |title=Statistical mechanics of chain molecules |year=1989 |publisher=Hanser Gardner |isbn=978-1-56990-019-2 |edition=Repr. corr.}}
*{{cite book |last=Gennes |first=Pierre-Gilles de |title=Scaling concepts in polymer physics |year=1996 |publisher=Cornell Univ. Press |location=Ithaca, New York |isbn=978-0-8014-1203-5 |edition=5. print.}} *{{cite book |last=Doi |first=M. |title=The theory of polymer dynamics |year=1988 |publisher=Clarendon Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-0-19-852033-7 |edition=Reprinted |author2=Edwards, S.F. }}
==Electromagnetism== {{See also|Electromagnetism|History of electromagnetism}} *[[William Gilbert (astronomer)|William Gilbert]] (main author), Aaron Dowling, 1600. : See [[#geophysics|geophysics]] section.
* [[Charles-Augustin de Coulomb|Coulomb, C. A.]] (1785–89). ''Mémoires sur l'Électricité et le Magnétisme'' (In French; trans. Memoirs on Electricity and Magnetism), a series of seven memoirs. : Contains descriptions empirical investigations into electricity. Established an empirical [[inverse-square law]] that would be named for him,<ref>Coulomb (1785a) [https://books.google.com/books?id=by5EAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA569#v=onepage&q&f=false "Premier mémoire sur l’électricité et le magnétisme,"] ''Histoire de l'Académie Royale des Sciences'', pages 569-577.</ref><ref>Coulomb (1785b) [https://books.google.com/books?id=by5EAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA578#v=onepage&q&f=false "Second mémoire sur l’électricité et le magnétisme,"] ''Histoire de l'Académie Royale des Sciences'', pages 578-611.</ref><ref>Coulomb (1785c) [https://books.google.com/books?id=by5EAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA612#v=onepage&q&f=false "Troisième mémoire sur l’électricité et le magnétisme,"] ''Histoire de l'Académie Royale des Sciences'', pages 612-638.</ref><ref>Coulomb (1786) [https://books.google.com/books?id=5hAVAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA67#v=onepage&q&f=false "Quatrième mémoire sur l’électricité,"] ''Histoire de l'Académie Royale des Sciences'', pages 67-77.</ref><ref>Coulomb (1787) [https://books.google.com/books?id=0uIEAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA421#v=onepage&q&f=false "Cinquième mémoire sur l’électricité,"] ''Histoire de l'Académie Royale des Sciences'', pages 421-467.</ref><ref>Coulomb (1788) [https://books.google.com/books?id=my5EAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA619#v=onepage&q&f=false "Sixième mémoire sur l’électricité,"] ''Histoire de l'Académie Royale des Sciences'', pages 617-705.</ref><ref>Coulomb (1789) [https://books.google.com/books?id=XhEVAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA455#v=onepage&q&f=false "Septième mémoire sur l’électricité et le magnétisme,"] ''Histoire de l'Académie Royale des Sciences'', pages 455-505.</ref> by measuring the twist in a [[torsion balance]].<ref>Coulomb (1784) [https://books.google.com/books?id=SS5EAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA229#v=onepage&q&f=false "Recherches théoriques et expérimentales sur la force de torsion et sur l'élasticité des fils de metal," (Theoretical research and experimentation on torsion and the elasticity of metal wire)] ''Histoire de l'Académie Royale des Sciences'', pages 229-269.</ref> Cavendish would use a [[Cavendish experiment|similar method]] to estimate the value of [[Universal gravitational constant|Newton's constant G]].<ref>* {{Cite book |last=Cavendish |first=Henry |contribution=Experiments to Determine the Density of the Earth |year=1798 |editor-last=MacKenzie |editor-first=A. S. |title=Scientific Memoirs Vol.9: The Laws of Gravitation |publication-date=1900 |publisher=American Book Co. |pages=59–105 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=O58mAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA59 }} Online copy of Cavendish's 1798 paper, and other early measurements of gravitational constant. </ref>
*{{cite journal |last1=Biot |first1= |last2=Savart |trans-title=Note on magnetism of the Volta pile |first2= |title=Note sur le magnétisme de la pile de Volta |journal=[[Annales de chimie et de physique]] |year=1820 |volume= |series= |issue= |pages= |page= |language=French}} : Introduced the [[Biot–Savart law]], the [[magnetostatic]] analogue of Coulomb's law.
*{{Cite journal |author=Ampère, André-Marie |authorlink=Andre-Marie Ampere |title=Théorie mathématique des phénomènes électro-dynamiques: uniquement déduite de l'expérience |year=1826 |language=French |trans-title=Memoir on the Mathematical Theory of Electrodynamic Phenomena, Uniquely Deduced from Experience |publisher=Méquignon-Marvis}} Online links at [https://books.google.com/books?id=LzcVAAAAQAAJ Google eBooks] (accessed 2010-09-26), and [https://archive.org/details/thoriemathmatiq00ampgoog archived from the original] at the [[Internet Archive]]. : Introduced the famous [[Ampere's law|eponymous law]] for electric current. * Ohm, GS (1827). "Die galvanische Kette, mathematisch bearbeitet [tr., The Galvanic Circuit Investigated Mathematically]" (in German). TH Riemann, Berlin. : Announced the [[Ohm's law|now-famous circuital relation]] between voltage and current. * [[George Green (mathematician)|Green, George]] (1828). "[[An Essay on the Application of Mathematical Analysis to the Theories of Electricity and Magnetism]]", Nottingham.<ref>This essay can be found in [http://name.umdl.umich.edu/AAN8197.0001.001 '' Mathematical papers of the late George Green''], edited by N. M. Ferrers. Accessed 7 Dec 2012.</ref> : Essay conceived several key ideas, among them a theorem similar to the modern [[Green's theorem]], the idea of [[potential]] functions, and the concept of what are now called [[Green's function]]s. {{citation needed|date=February 2013}} This (initially obscure) work directly influenced the work of [[James Clerk Maxwell]] and [[William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin|William Thomson]], among others.
*{{cite book |last=Faraday |first=Michael |title=Experimental researches in electricity |year=1839–1855 |publisher=Green Lion Press |location=Santa Fe (N.M.) |isbn=978-1-888009-15-6 |edition=Reprinted 2000 from the 1st ed. 1839 (vol. 1), 1844 (vol. 2), 1855 (vol. 3)}} :[[Faraday's law of induction]] and research in [[electromagnetism]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bragg |first=Melvyn |title=12 books that changed the world |year=2006 |publisher=Hodder & Stoughton |location=London |isbn=978-0-340-83981-2}}</ref>
*{{Cite journal |first=James Clerk |last=Maxwell |author-link=James Clerk Maxwell |year=1861 |title=On Physical Lines of Force |journal=[[Philosophical Magazine|The London, Edinburgh, and Dublin Philosophical Magazine and Journal of Science]] |volume=21 |issue=4 |pages=161&ndash;175; 281&ndash;291; 338&ndash;348 |doi=|title-link=On Physical Lines of Force }} *{{cite book |first=James Clerk |last=Maxwell |author-link=James Clerk Maxwell |title=A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field |editor-first=Thomas F. |editor-last=Torrance |others=1982 reprint, with an appreciation by Albert Einstein |year=1865 |publisher=Wipf and Stock |location=Eugene, Oregon |isbn=978-1-57910-015-5|title-link=A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field }} :The third of [[James Clerk Maxwell]]'s papers concerned with [[electromagnetism]]. The concept of [[displacement current]] was introduced, so that it became possible to derive equations of [[electromagnetic wave]]. It was the first [[paper]] in which [[Maxwell's equations]] appeared.
* Hall, E.H. (1879). "On a New Action of the Magnet on Electric Currents". American Journal of Mathematics vol 2, p.&nbsp;287-292. Thesis (PhD), Johns Hopkins U. : Details an experimental analysis of [[Hall effect|voltaic effect later named for author]]. *{{cite book |first=J. D. |last=Jackson |author-link=John David Jackson (physicist) |title=Classical Electrodynamics |publisher=Wiley |edition=3rd |year=1998 |isbn=978-0-471-30932-1}} :The defining graduate-level introductory text. (First edition 1962)
