*{{cite journal |first=Edward N. |last=Lorenz |author-link=Edward N. Lorenz |title=Deterministic Nonperiodic Flow |year=1963 |journal=[[Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences]] |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=130&ndash;141 |doi=10.1175/1520-0469(1963)020<0130:DNF>2.0.CO;2 |bibcode=1963JAtS...20..130L |issn=1520-0469 }} :A finite system of deterministic nonlinear [[ordinary differential equations]] is introduced to represent forced dissipative [[fluid dynamics|hydrodynamic flow]], simulating simple phenomena in the real atmosphere. All of the solutions are found to be unstable, and most of them nonperiodic, thus forcing to reevaluate the feasibility of long-term weather prediction. In this paper the [[Lorenz attractor]] is presented for the first time, and gave the first hint of what is now known as [[butterfly effect]].
*{{cite journal |title=Period Three Implies Chaos |first=Tien-Yien |last=Li |author-link=James A. Yorke |first2=James A. |last2=Yorke |journal=The American Mathematical Monthly |year=1975 |volume=82 |issue=10 |pages=985&ndash;992 |doi=10.2307/2318254 |jstor=2318254|citeseerx=10.1.1.329.5038 }}
==Optics== {{See also|Optics|History of optics}}
*{{cite book |last=Alhacen |author-link=Alhazen |title=Book of Optics |year=1021|title-link=Book of Optics }} : ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]: ''Kitab al-Manazir'', [[Latin]]: ''De Aspectibus'') &ndash; a seven volume treatise on [[optics]] and [[physics]], written by [[Ibn al-Haytham]] (Latinized as ''Alhacen'' or ''Alhazen'' in Europe), and published in 1021.
* {{Cite journal |first=R |last=Hooke |author-link=Robert Hooke |title=Micrographia: or, Some physiological descriptions of minute bodies made by magnifying glasses |location=London |publisher=J. Martyn and J. Allestry |year=1665 |edition=first|title-link=Micrographia }} : The first major publication of the [[Royal Society]]. It generated a wide public interest in, and often is considered the creator of, the science of [[microscopy]]. Also notable for coining the term "[[biological cell]]".
*{{cite book |first=Christiaan |last=Huygens |author-link=Christiaan Huygens |title=Traité de la Lumiere |trans-title=Treatise on Light |year=1690}} :Huygens attained a remarkably clear understanding of the principles of wave-propagation; and his exposition of the subject marks an epoch in the treatment of Optical problems. Not appreciated until much later due to the mistaken zeal with which formerly everything that conflicted with the cherished ideas of Newton was denounced by his followers.
*{{cite book |first=Christiaan |last=Huygens |author-link=Christiaan Huygens |title=Dioptrica |year=1703}} :This posthumous publication contains the law of refraction (now known as "Snell's law) and was partly based on unpublished observations that [[Willebrord Snellius]] made and wrote in 1621.
*{{cite book |first=Isaac |last=Newton |author-link=Isaac Newton |title=Opticks or, a Treatise of the reflexions, refractions, inflexions and colours of light. Also two treatises of the species and magnitude of curvilinear figures |location=London |publisher=printed for Sam. Smith. and Benj. Walford |year=1704 |title-link=Opticks }} [http://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb36118888z (available online)] : A key publication in the history of physics, arguably Newton's second most influential physics publication after ''Principia''. Within he describes his famous experiments regarding colour and light, and ends with a set of [[the Queries|queries]] about the nature of light and matter.
*{{cite book |last=Goethe |first=Johann Wolfgang von |author-link=Johann Wolfgang von Goethe |title=Zur Farbenlehre |trans-title=(On the) [[Theory of Colours]] |year=1970 |publisher=MIT Press |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |language=German |isbn=978-0-262-57021-3 |edition=Reprint London 1840 |others=Translated from the German, with notes, by Charles Lock Eastlake ; introduction by Deane B. Judd |origyear=1810}} : Seminal text (regarded as polemical for its time) that influenced later research on human visual and colour perception,<ref>[[Ernst Ising|Ising, E]]; [http://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/anglica/Chronology/20thC/Ising/isi_goet.html Goethe as a Physicist - bibliotheca Augustana]. Volume 18 (4) American Association of Physics Teachers – Apr 1, 1950. Accessed 26 Jul 2013.</ref> from an author usually remembered for his literary work. *{{cite journal| last=Young| first=Thomas| title=Bakerian Lecture: Experiments and calculations relative to physical optics|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society|year=1804|volume=94|pages = 1–16 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7AZGAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false|bibcode = 1804RSPT...94....1Y| doi=10.1098/rstl.1804.0001}} *{{Cite book |last=Fresnel |first=Augustin |author-link=Augustin Fresnel |year=1819 |chapter=Memoir on the Diffraction of Light |title=The Wave Theory of Light – Memoirs by Huygens, Young and Fresnel |publisher=American Book Company |pages=79–145 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_0hWAAAAMAAJ&dq=memoir%20of%20fresnel&pg=PA79#v=onepage&q&f=false}} *{{Cite book |last=Fresnel |first=Augustin |author-link=Augustin Fresnel |year=1819 |chapter=On the Action of Rays of Polarized Light upon Each Other |title=The Wave Theory of Light – Memoirs by Huygens, Young and Fresnel |publisher=American Book Company |pages=145–156 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=_0hWAAAAMAAJ&dq=memoir%20of%20fresnel&pg=PA145#v=onepage&q&f=false}} :Work by Thomas Young and Fresnel provided a comprehensive picture of the propagation of light.
* Hamiltonian geometrical optics. ''Theory of Systems of Rays'' and three supplements. Reissued in {{cite book |first=William Rowan |last=Hamilton |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ekPnMgEACAAJ |title=The Mathematical Papers of Sir William Rowan Hamilton, Volume I: Geometrical Optics |others=Edited for the Royal Irish Academy by A. W. Conway and J. L. Synge |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=1931 |accessdate=2013-07-13}} ** {{cite journal | last1 = Hamilton | first1 = W.R. | year = 1828 | title = Theory of Systems of Rays | url = | journal = Transactions of the Royal Irish Academy | volume = 15 | issue = | pages = 69–174 }} **——. "Supplement to an Essay on the Theory of Systems of Rays" (''Transactions of the Royal Irish Academy'', volume 16, part 1 (1830), pp.&nbsp;1–61.) **——. "Second Supplement to an Essay on the Theory of Systems of Rays" (''Transactions of the Royal Irish Academy'', volume 16, part 2 (1831), pp.&nbsp;93–125.) **——. "Third Supplement to an Essay on the Theory of Systems of Rays" (''Transactions of the Royal Irish Academy'', volume 17 (1837), pp.&nbsp;1–144.) : A series of papers recording [[Hamiltonian optics|Hamilton's work in geometric optics]].<ref>D.R. Wilkins, [http://www.maths.tcd.ie/pub/HistMath/People/Hamilton/Optics.html Hamilton's Papers on Geometrical Optics]. [[Trinity College Dublin School of Mathematics|School of Mathematics]], [[Trinity College Dublin]]. Accessed 13 Jul 2013.</ref> This would later become an inspiration for Hamiltonian mechanics. *[[James Clerk Maxwell|Maxwell, James Clerk]] (1861), (1865). : See [[#electromagnetism|electromagnetism]] section.
*{{cite journal |last=Udem |first=Th. |author2=Reichert, J. |author3=Holzwarth, R. |author4=Hänsch, T. W. |title=Accurate measurement of large optical frequency differences with a mode-locked laser |journal=Optics Letters |year=1999 |volume=24 |issue=13 |page=881 |doi=10.1364/OL.24.000881 |url=http://www.mpq.mpg.de/~haensch/comb/people/thomas/OL99.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100804120440/http://www.mpq.mpg.de/~haensch/comb/people/thomas/OL99.pdf |archivedate=2010-08-04 |format=PDF |bibcode=1999OptL...24..881U }} *{{cite journal |last=Reichert |first=J. |author2=T. W. Hänsch |title=Measuring the frequency of light with mode-locked lasers |journal=Optics Communications |year=1999 |volume=172 |issue=1–6 |pages=59–68 |doi=10.1016/S0030-4018(99)00491-5 |bibcode=1999OptCo.172...59R|authorlink2=Theodor W. Hänsch |last3=Udem |first3=Th. |last4=Hänsch |first4=T. W. }} *{{cite journal |last=Udem |first=Th. |author2=Holzwarth, R. |author3=Hänsch, T. W. |title=Optical frequency metrology |journal=Nature |year=2002 |volume=416 |issue=6877 |pages=233–237 |doi=10.1038/416233a |bibcode=2002Natur.416..233U |pmid=11894107 }} :These three papers introduced the [[Frequency comb]] technique. The earlier presented the main idea but last is the one often cited.
==Nuclear and particle physics== ===Nuclear physics=== {{main|Nuclear physics}} *{{cite journal|author=Becquerel, H|author-link=Henri Becquerel|title =Sur les radiations émises par phosphorescence|journal=Comptes Rendus |volume = 122| pages = 420–421|year=1896|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k30780/f422.chemindefer}} : Reported the accidental discovery of [[radioactivity|a new kind of radiation]]. Awarded the 1903 Nobel Prize in Physics for this work. *[[Ernest Rutherford|Rutherford, E.]] (2004; first ed. 1904). ''Radio-activity''. Courier Dover Publications, 399 pages. {{ISBN|048649585X}}, 9780486495859. *{{cite journal |author=Hess, V. F. |author-link=Victor F. Hess |year=1912 |language=German |trans-title=About Observations of penetrating Radiation during seven balloon-journeys |title=Über Beobachtungen der durchdringenden Strahlung bei sieben Freiballonfahrten |journal=Physikalische Zeitschrift |volume=13 |issue= |pages=1084–1091 |doi= }} : Gives an account of the author's discovery of high energy cosmic radiation. Awarded half of the 1936 Nobel Prize in Physics. * Neutron discovery. **{{Cite journal| last1 = Chadwick | first1 = J.| authorlink = James Chadwick| title = Possible Existence of a Neutron| doi = 10.1038/129312a0| journal = Nature| volume = 129| issue = 3252| pages = 312| year = 1932| pmid = | pmc = |bibcode = 1932Natur.129Q.312C }} **{{Cite journal| last1 = Chadwick | first1 = J.| authorlink = James Chadwick| title = The Existence of a Neutron| doi = 10.1098/rspa.1932.0112| journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences| volume = 136| issue = 830| pages = 692–708| year = 1932| pmid = | pmc = |bibcode = 1932RSPSA.136..692C }} **{{Cite journal| last1 = Chadwick | first1 = J.| authorlink = James Chadwick| title = Bakerian Lecture. The Neutron| doi = 10.1098/rspa.1933.0152| journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences| volume = 142| issue = 846| pages = 1–26| year = 1933| pmid = | pmc = |bibcode = 1933RSPSA.142....1C }} :Chadwick's experiments confirmed the identity of the mysterious particle detected independently by Joliot-Curie & Joliot,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Joliot-Curie, Irène |author2=Joliot, Frédéric |lastauthoramp=yes|url=http://visualiseur.bnf.fr/CadresFenetre?O=NUMM-3147&I=1236 |title=Émission de protons de grande vitesse par les substances hydrogénées sous l'influence des rayons ? très pénétrants |trans-title=Emission of high-speed protons by hydrogenated substances under the influence of very penetrating ?-rays |volume=194 |page=273 |year=1932 |journal=Comptes Rendus}}</ref> and Bothe & Becker<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF01390908 |title=Künstliche Erregung von Kern-?-Strahlen |trans-title=Artificial excitation of nuclear ?-radiation |year=1930 |last1=Bothe |first1=W. |last2=Becker |first2=H. |journal=Zeitschrift für Physik |volume=66 |issue=5–6 |pages=289–306 |bibcode=1930ZPhy...66..289B }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF01336726 |title=Die in Bor und Beryllium erregten ?-Strahlen |trans-title=G-rays excited in boron and beryllium |year=1932 |last1=Becker |first1=H. |last2=Bothe |first2=W. |journal=Zeitschrift für Physik |volume=76 |issue=7–8 |pages=421–438 |bibcode=1932ZPhy...76..421B }}</ref> and predicted by Majorana and others<ref>[[Viktor Ambartsumian|Ambartsumian]] and [[Dmitri Ivanenko|Ivanenko]] (1930) "Об одном следствии теории дирака протонов и электронов" (On a Consequence of the Dirac Theory of Protons and Electrons), Доклады Академии Наук СССР (Doklady Akademii Nauk SSSR / Proceedings of the USSR Academy of Sciences) Ser. A, no. 6, pages 153-155. [http://ambartsumian.ru/dvd/Publications/Papers/1930DANSSSR___153A.pdf Available in Russian on-line.]</ref> to be [[neutron|a neutral nucleon]] in 1932, for which Chadwick was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] in 1935.<ref>[http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1935/chadwick-bio.html James Chadwick - Biography]</ref>
* {{citation|title=Trends to a theory of beta radiation|author= E. Fermi|journal= Nuovo Cimento |volume=11 |issue= 1|year=1934|pages= 1–19|doi=10.1007/bf02959820|bibcode=1934NCim...11....1F}}. In Italian. : Introduced a [[Fermi theory of beta decay|theory of beta decay]], which first appeared in 1933.<ref>"Tentativo di una teoria dei raggi β" (in Italian) [A tentative Theory of β-rays], Ricerca Scientifica, 1933.</ref> The article was later translated into German,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fermi | first1 = E | year = 1934 | title = Versuch einer Theorie der beta-Strahlen. (Search for a Theory of beta-Rays) [German] | url = | journal = Zeitschrift für Physik | volume = 88 | issue = 3–4| page = 161 | doi=10.1007/bf01351864| bibcode = 1934ZPhy...88..161F}}</ref> and much later English,<ref>{{Cite web | last = Fermi | first = E. | title = Fermi's Theory of Beta Decay (English translation by Fred L. Wilson, 1968) | website = [[American Journal of Physics]] | year = 1934 | url = http://microboone-docdb.fnal.gov/cgi-bin/RetrieveFile?docid=953;filename=FermiBetaDecay1934.pdf;version=1 }}</ref> having been refused publication in [[Nature (journal)|Nature]]. This was later influential in understanding the [[weak nuclear force]]. *Bethe ''Nuclear Physics'' papers **{{cite journal |last=Bethe |first=Hans |author2=R. F. Bacher |title=Nuclear Physics. A: Stationary States of Nuclei |journal=Reviews of Modern Physics |year=1936 |volume=8 |pages=82&ndash;229 |bibcode=1936RvMP....8...82B |doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.8.82 |issue=2}} **{{cite journal |last=Bethe |first=Hans |title=Nuclear Physics. B: Nuclear Dynamics, Theoretical |journal=Reviews of Modern Physics |year=1937 |volume=9 |pages=69&ndash;244 |bibcode=1937RvMP....9...69B |doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.9.69 |issue=2}} **{{cite journal |last=Bethe |first=Hans |author2=M. Stanley Livingston |title=Nuclear Physics. C: Nuclear Dynamics, Experimental |journal=Reviews of Modern Physics |year=1937 |volume=9 |pages=245&ndash;390 |bibcode=1937RvMP....9..245L |doi=10.1103/RevModPhys.9.245 |issue=3 }} :A series of three articles by [[Hans Bethe]] summarizing the knowledge in the subject of Nuclear Physics at the time of publication. The set of three articles is colloquially referred to as "Bethe's bible".
*{{cite journal |author=C. L. Cowan, Jr., F. Reines, F. B. Harrison, H. W. Kruse, A. D. McGuire |title=Detection of the Free Neutrino: a Confirmation |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=124 |issue=3212 |pages=103–4 |bibcode=1956Sci...124..103C |doi=10.1126/science.124.3212.103 |pmid=17796274 |date=July 20, 1956 |last2=Reines |last3=Harrison |last4=Kruse |last5=McGuire }} :This contains an account of an [[Cowan–Reines neutrino experiment|experiment]] first suggested by Wang,<ref> {{cite journal |author=K.-C. Wang |year=1942 |title=A Suggestion on the Detection of the Neutrino |journal=[[Physical Review]] |volume=61 |issue=1–2 |page=97 |bibcode=1942PhRv...61...97W |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.61.97 }}</ref> confirming the existence of a particle (the neutrino, more precisely the electron neutrino) first predicted by Pauli in 1940;<ref>As written in his famous letter to the Physical Institute of the [[Federal Institute of Technology]], [[Zürich]], on 4 Dec 1940. </ref><ref> {{Cite journal |author=L.M. Brown |year=1978 |title=The idea of the neutrino |journal=[[Physics Today]] |volume=31 |issue=9 |pages=23–28 |doi=10.1063/1.2995181 |bibcode = 1978PhT....31i..23B }}</ref> a result that was rewarded almost forty years later with the [[Nobel Prize in Physics|1995 Nobel Prize]] for Reines.<ref name="noblp"> {{cite web |accessdate=29 June 2010 |title=The Nobel Prize in Physics 1995 |url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1995/ |publisher=[[The Nobel Foundation]] }}</ref>
* Wu et al. (1957) :See [[#particle physics|particle physics]] section. *Fowler et al. (1957). :See [[#astrophysics|astrophysics]] section.
===Particle physics=== {{main|Particle physics}} * Thomson, JJ (1897). : See the [[#Atomic and molecular physics|atomic and molecular physics]] section. *Hess, V. F. (1912). : See the [[#Nuclear physics|nuclear physics]] section. *{{cite journal |author=C.D. Anderson |year=1932 |title=The Apparent Existence of Easily Deflectable Positives |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=76 |issue=1967 |pages=238–9 |doi=10.1126/science.76.1967.238 |pmid=17731542 |bibcode=1932Sci....76..238A }} : Experimental detection of the [[positron]] verifying the prediction from the Dirac equation, for which Anderson won the Nobel Physics prize in 1936. '''See also''': {{cite journal |author=C.D. Anderson |year=1933 |title=The Positive Electron |journal=[[Physical Review]] |volume=43 |pages=491–494 |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.43.491 |bibcode=1933PhRv...43..491A |issue=6 }} * Fermi, E. (1934). : See the [[#Nuclear physics|nuclear physics]] section. * J.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Street and E.&nbsp;C.&nbsp;Stevenson. "New Evidence for the Existence of a Particle Intermediate Between the Proton and Electron", Phys. Rev. 52, 1003 (1937). :Experimental confirmation of a particle first discovered by Anderson and Neddermeyer at Caltech in 1936;<ref>[http://www.aip.org/history/ohilist/4487.html Oral History interview transcript with Carl D. Anderson 30 June 1966, American Institute of Physics, Niels Bohr Library and Archives] </ref> originally thought to be Yukawa's meson,<ref>Yukaya Hideka, On the Interaction of Elementary Particles 1, Proceedings of the Physico-Mathematical Society of Japan (3) 17, 48, pp 139–148 (1935). (Read 17 November 1934)</ref> but later shown to be a "heavy electron", now called [[muon]].
* Cowan et al. (1956) : See the [[#Nuclear physics|nuclear physics]] section.
* {{cite journal |last1=Wu |first1=C. S. |last2=Ambler |first2=E |last3=Hayward |first3=R. W. |last4=Hoppes |first4=D. D. |last5=Hudson |first5=R. P. |year=1957 |title=Experimental Test of Parity Conservation in Beta Decay |journal=[[Physical Review]] |volume=105 |issue=4 |pages=1413–1415 |bibcode=1957PhRv..105.1413W |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.105.1413 }} : An [[The Wu Experiment|important experiment]] (based on a theoretical analysis by Lee and Yang<ref> {{cite journal |last1=Lee |first1=T. D. |last2=Yang |first2=C. N. |year=1956 |title=Question of Parity Conservation in Weak Interactions |journal=[[Physical Review]] |volume=104 |issue=1 |pages=254–258 |bibcode=1956PhRv..104..254L |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.104.254 }}</ref>) that proved that [[parity violation|parity conservation was disobeyed]] by the weak force, later confirmed by another group in the same year.<ref> {{cite journal |last1=Garwin |first1=R. L. |last2=Lederman |first2=L. M. |last3=Weinrich |first3=M. |year=1957 |title=Observations of the Failure of Conservation of Parity and Charge Conjugation in Meson Decays: The Magnetic Moment of the Free Muon |journal=[[Physical Review]] |volume=105 |issue=4 |pages=1415–1417 |bibcode=1957PhRv..105.1415G |doi=10.1103/PhysRev.105.1415 }}</ref> This won Lee and Yang the Nobel Prize in Physics for 1957.
