*{{cite book |first=J. Willard |last=Gibbs |authorlink=Willard Gibbs |year=1875–1878 |title=On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances |publisher=Connecticut Acad. Sci. |isbn=978-0-8493-9685-4|title-link=On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances }} Reprinted in: **{{cite book |first=J. Willard |last=Gibbs |author-mask=1 |date=October 1993 |title=The Scientific Papers of J. Willard Gibbs (Vol. 1) |publisher=Ox Bow Press |isbn=978-0-918024-77-0 }} **{{cite book |first=J. Willard |last=Gibbs |author-mask=1 |date=February 1994 |title=The Scientific Papers of J. Willard Gibbs (Vol. 2) |publisher=Ox Bow Press |isbn=978-1-881987-06-2 }} :Between 1876 and 1878 Gibbs wrote a series of papers collectively entitled "''On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances''", considered one of the greatest achievements in physical science in the 19th century and the foundation of the science of [[physical chemistry]]. In these papers Gibbs applied [[thermodynamics]] to the interpretation of physicochemical phenomena and showed the explanation and interrelationship of what had been known only as isolated, inexplicable facts. Gibbs' papers on heterogeneous equilibria included: some [[chemical potential]] concepts; some [[Thermodynamic free energy|free energy]] concepts; a [[statistical ensemble|Gibbsian ensemble]] ideal (basis of the [[statistical mechanics]] field); and a ''[[Gibbs phase rule|phase rule]]''.
